{{use mdy dates|date=August 2013}} {{Infobox award | name = Donaldson Awards | image = | alt = | caption = | description = [[Broadway theatre]] | sponsor = | date = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | location = [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]] | country = United States | reward = Gold key and a scroll | year = {{start date and age|1944|p=yes}} | year2 = {{end date and age|1955|p=yes}} }}
The '''Donaldson Awards''' were a set of theatre awards established in 1944 by the drama critic [[Robert Francis (critic)|Robert Francis]]<ref name=lisa/> in honor of W. H. Donaldson (1864–1925), the founder of ''The Billboard'' (now ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'') magazine.
Categories included "best new play", "best new musical", "best performance", "best debut" and "best costumes and set design". The winners were chosen by votes of the theatre community at large with no predetermined nominees and the winners were presented with a gold key and a scroll.<ref name=lisa>Sagolla, Lisa Jo (2003). ''The Girl Who Fell Down{{spaced ndash}} A Biography of Joan McCracken''. Boston: [[University Press of New England]]. {{ISBN|978-1-555-53573-5}}. p. 107.</ref>
According to an article in ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', "The Donaldson Awards are the stages' accolades to their own."<ref>Francis, Robert (April 27, 1946). [https://books.google.com/books?id=9BkEAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA36&dq=%22Donaldson%20Awards%20%22&pg=PA36#v=onepage&q=%22Donaldson%20Awards%20%22&f=false "Revivals in New Donaldson Awards"]. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|The Billboard]]''.</ref>
The awards were discontinued in 1955 having been overshadowed by the Antoinette Perry Awards ([[Tony Awards]]).<ref>Bordman, Gerald Martin; Hischak, Thomas S. (2004). ''The Oxford Companion to American Theatre''. New York City; Oxford: [[Oxford University Press]]. {{ISBN|978-0-195-16986-7}}. p. 183.</ref>
==List of winners== <ref>Eligibility List for 12th Annual Donaldson Awards (containing previous winners) & [https://books.google.com/books?id=NyMEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4&dq=1955+donaldson+award+winners,&source=bl&ots=znSA3JMHDF&sig=h4tdZPg93RC_0z75yi1F3w4ebnw&hl=en&ei=s6DWTuO3A4bk0QHEjPGQCA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=1&sqi=2&ved=0CB8Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=1955%20donaldson%20award%20winners%2C&f=false "Award Winners, 1954&ndash;55 Season"]. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. July 9, 1955.</ref>
<small>(Note: on occasion a single performance won in multiple categories, such as Nanette Fabray winning as both actress and supporting actress for ''High Button Shoes''.)</small>
